article.description:
Elaine Powell scored a 
season-high 16 points to lead a balanced attack as the Detroit
Shock defeated the Seattle Storm, 74-61.
article.headline: Powell, Cash lead Shock in quashing Storm
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Elaine Powell's worries might be over, and that's good news for the Detroit Shock. Powell scored 16 points and Swin Cash added 15 as the Detroit Shock defeated the Seattle Storm 74-61 Friday night. "I've been struggling a little bit, so this is a big confidence builder for me," Powell said. "We really needed this one to build our lead back to where we had it at early in the season." Deanna Nolan added 12 points and Cheryl Ford had 11 rebounds for the Shock. Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer was happy to beat talented Seattle. "Swin got us off to a great start," Laimbeer said. "We weren't always fluid and we had some lulls, but any win against that team is a good win." Seattle's Lauren Jackson led all scorers with 23 points, and Sue Bird added 14. Detroit led 34-31 at the half behind nine points from Cash. Bird had 10 for Seattle. The Storm were still within three, 42-39, with 13 minutes to play, but the Shock went on an 11-2 run to take a 12-point lead with 8:59 to go. Nolan had five points in the surge. With Bird on the bench with a sore knee, the Shock outscored Seattle 14-5 in the final four minutes. "My knee has been bothering me off and on all season," said Bird, who played just eight minutes in the second half. "When it doesn't hurt, I'm 100 percent, but when I tweak it like I did tonight, I really can't move at all. It is frustrating to be on the floor and know you are hurting your team." The margin was 13 points when Jackson started Seattle's comeback. She hit three 3-pointers in less than three minutes, and had 11 points in a 13-4 run that brought the Storm within 60-56 with 3:59 left. Powell, though, scored the next four points and the Shock pulled away for the victory.
Game notes
Bird was limping throughout the second half with a sore left knee, and only played eight minutes after halftime. ... Detroit guard Kedra Holland-Corn left the game with a sprained right hand. ... Cash and Bird were teammates on Connecticut's undefeated 2002 national title team. ... Nolan left the game in the final three minutes after hitting her head on the floor, but was not seriously injured.
